replies.bodyText:
Is there a point going for all the checks in isAssignable when we know eventually it will call isArrayTypesAssignable function anyway?

L779 and L782 check assignability for the element types of the first level of arrays. And the element types may or may not be array types, so we can't say for sure it'll be calling isArrayTypesAssignable.
Consider
string[] s = [];
(string|int)[] t = s;
For (string|int)[] t = s;, isArrayTypesAssignable gets invoked first, which then at L779 calls isArrayTypesAssignable again with source string and target (string|int) which eventually ends up calling isAssignable like in L807. Instead, we can directly call  isAssignable to check assignability of element types.

And changing the first parameter to BArrayType makes this specific right?

IMO, the name isArrayTypesAssignable itself has already made it specific. :) This IS a specific check right?
Basically we call this method only when the source type is an array, to check if it is assignable to a specific type.
So rhsType is always an array.

if lhsType is also an array - return isAssignable(rhsElemType, lhsElemType)
if lhsType is a union - return true if for at least one member isArrayTypesAssignable is true
if lhsType is json - return isAssignable(rhsElemType, lhsType)
if lhsType is anydata - return rhsType.isAnydata()
if lhsType is any - return rhsElemType.tag != TypeTags.ERROR

timeline.body:
For unions, consider something like,

```ballerina
   int[] x = [1, 2];
   int|string[] y = x;
```

The current check will cause this assignment to pass right?

I think for unions we have to check `isArrayTypesAssignable` individually for each member and return true if at least one returns true.

```java
        if (target.tag == TypeTags.UNION) {
            for (BType memberType : ((BUnionType) target).getMemberTypes()) {
                if (isArrayTypesAssignable(source, memberType, unresolvedTypes) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
            return false;
        }
```

